@NODE Introduction "What is GRaBAtOR good for?"

  @{b}Introduction:@{ub}

    First of all, sorry for my English, it isn't my native language.

    I damaged an audio-CD from a friend of mine (physically).  I'm not sure
    about it, was it really me.  However, I decided to create an
    100%-exact-copy of that CD and give it back to him.  Unfortunately I
    couldn't find any tool that could rip those damaged tracks 100%
    error-free (even with my UltraPlex).  So I decided to write GRaBAtOR...

    GRaBAtOR is a utility to read tracks from audio-CDs *absolutely
    error-free*@{"Ļ" LINK ErrorFree}.

    GRaBAtOR is intended for making mp3's and/or writing audio-CDs without
    errors@{"Ļ" LINK ErrorFree} (which could cause audible distortions).

    GRaBAtOR is in first place ment for people who don't know much about
    (digital)-audio, but neverthless want good results when reading CDDA.


  @{b}Description:@{ub}

    - GRaBAtOR can read damaged audio-CDs *error-free*@{"Ļ" LINK ErrorFree}

    - GRaBAtOR can read audio-CDs *error-free*@{"Ļ" LINK ErrorFree} with a drive which normally
    doesn't deliver very good CDDA-data

    - With GRaBAtOR you don't have to check twice for every track you rip (
    e.g., you don't have to listen to the ripped tracks, this is normally
    plus 1x realtime, which is normally sufficient for GRaBAtOR)

    - GRaBAtOR is ideal for very bad CDs in conjunction with a little script
    (see @{" Usage " LINK Usage 27}) and much, much time (overnight).  :-) (see @{" Drawbacks " LINK Drawbacks 4})

    To make things clear, GRaBAtOR was in first place designed for a
    good-quality audio-output, not for speed and/or memory-usage.  Although,
    it will be faster in future versions and it will need less memory.


  @{b}Note:@{ub}

    Neverthless it *is* possible to damage a disc so much that even GRaBAtOR
    cannot read data of that (error-free).  Take care of your CDs.  *sigh*

@ENDNODE
@NODE Quickstart "For people in a hurry  :)"

  @{b}Quickstart:@{ub}

    - Check first if your miggy suits GRaBAtOR's needs @{" here " LINK Requirements 0}.

    - Installation isn't required, you may use the program from where it is.

    - Insert an audio-CD, from which you were not able to read CDDA-data
    error-free until now in your CDROM

    - Open a CLI, CD to the dir where GRaBAtOR resides, and type something like this:

      GRaBAtOR DEVICE oktagon.device UNIT 5 DH3:Track06.aiff START TRACK 6
                      ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^      ^ ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^             ^
      (Replace these (^) values with your own values.)

    - If your drive isn't supported yet, you have to specify DRIVEISLSB or
    DRIVEISMSB as well, depending which on kind of data your drive delivers.
    In most cases you will use DRIVEISLSB here, but if you get nothing than
    noise, you probably have to specify DRIVEISMSB.

    - If something went wrong, you can stop GRaBAtOR with CTRL-c.

    - The result should be in file DH3:Track06.aiff (or with what you
    replaced this file) after a certain amount of time.

    - Play it with with your favourite AIFF-player, and hear the difference.
    :)

  Back to @{" Main " LINK Main}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Features "GRaBAtOR's features"

  @{b}Features:@{ub}

    - Error-free@{"Ļ" LINK ErrorFree} rips!
    - Strips off leading and trailing zeroes!  (can be omitted, enabled by
    default) If you like (more) zeroes between the audio-tracks (than
    normally), burn some on your brand new CD with your favourite
    CDR-software.
    - Rips the tracks either STEREO, LEFT channel only, RIGHT channel only
    or both channels JOINED!
    - Keeps track of the CDDA-byte-order of some CDROM-models (of course you
    can adjust it manually too)
    - Short ( < 40kB )
    - 1000x faster than reading and listening and reading and listening and
    reading and listening and ...  those really bad discs!
    - Many options
    - Extreme user-friendly (self-explaining parameters)
    - Easy-to-use - Specify only the parameters you need
    - You can specify all positions by TRACKnumber, TIME and BLOCKs, you can
    even mix them all.  (see first note on the position parameter @{" here " LINK Usage 137})
    E.g.  if you want to rip exactly the first 10 seconds from the third
    song, you would type:  'GRaBAtOR <outfile> START TRACK 3 LENGTH TIME
    0:10:00' (see @{" Usage " LINK Usage})
    - Default options produce the best posible results with most
    configurations (with quality in mind, not speed).
    - GRaBAtOR is foolproof (I hope :-).  You'll practically rip what you
    really wanted to rip.  :-)
    - supported formats:
      - AIFF (default)
      - CDDA (Motorola + intel)
      - WAVE (not implemented (yet?)
    - Output can either be a file or stdout (stdout disabled yet due to some
    bugs combined with lazyness)
    - Automatically continues rip (can be omitted) (e.g. in case of a reboot)
    - Should support Pipe:  as well (e.g.  to redirect the GRaBAtOR's output
    to your favourite MP3-encoder) (not tested yet)
    - CLI only.  Yes, this is a feature.  :-) 
    - Calculates amount of bad data written to output
    - Amiga-style argument parsing.  (e.g.:  type 'GRaBAtOR ?' for help)
    - You can stop GRaBAtOR with CTRL-c.
    - Definitely no PC version available!  ;-)

  ...and all this for free!  (see @{" About " LINK About})

  (see also @{" ToDo " LINK ToDo})

@ENDNODE
@NODE ErrorFree "ErrorFree"

  Ļ: (optionally as as error-free as possible) (see @{" Usage " LINK Usage 200})

@ENDNODE
@NODE Important "Important notes"

  @{b}Under development:@{ub}

    GRaBAtOR and it's documentation are in a beta state and under
    development.  So it might come that the program does not do (exactly)
    what you (or I) (or both of us) expected.  Anyway, as GRaBAtOR only
    reads from a device and writes to files, I expect nothing to go wrong,
    e.g.  it should not be able to destroy your HD, etc.


  @{b}NOERRORBUG:@{ub}

    Read all about the NOERRORBUG option in the @{" Usage " LINK Usage 85} section!


  @{b}Overheat:@{ub}

    As some drives seem to overheat during extensive readings, I've
    implemented a special feature in GRaBAtOR.  It simply stops the motor
    end ejects the tray (supposed your drive has a tray), and waits a
    certain amount of time.  In some cases this helps *a lot* in reading
    data from the drive error-free.  (E.g.  the disc(s) in my Sony CDROM
    sometimes becomes very hot, and under such conditions the drive doesn't
    give best possible results anymore (especially on damaged discs).  This
    didn't happened with my Plextor yet, though.)
    Because some drives give *much* better results with this "cooling"
    feature, I decided to turn it ON by default.

    If you think this is annoying, and/or your drive won't overheat at all,
    you can of course disable this behaviour with the option NOEJECT, or
    even NOSTOP.  At least you should test this feature, whether it's worth
    it or not.

    Note:  This feature won't turn in action at all until a really big error
    occurs.

    (Currently this feature isn't implemented at all, so don't bother.)


  @{b}More:@{ub}

  ∑ If you continue an old file, then make sure, that you are using the same
    options than when the file was created!  Although GRaBAtOR _tries_ to find
    out some of the previous options.

  ∑ Never try to continue a file made with an older version of GRaBAtOR!


  (see also @{"Disclaimer" LINK Disclaimer})

@ENDNODE
@NODE Drawbacks "Disadvantages and Limitations"

  @{b}Drawbacks:@{ub}

    - 3-4x slower than other programs, even slower on faulty discs (quality
    has it's price...).  But you can usually still expect to rip
    audio-tracks in approx.  realtime.  (Speed depends mainly on the CDROM's
    ability how fast it can send CDDA to the SCSI-bus.  Currently it also
    depends on your mem's speed, as the program actually needs and uses much
    more RAM than needed.)

    - No GUI.

    - No PPC-version available.  Don't misuse your PPC for ripping
    CDDA-data.  (In the future GRaBAtOR will be faster, however.)

    - Error-checking is _always_ on, which means GRaBAtOR _is_ (and probably
    will ever be) always slower than simple CDDA-readers.  If you don't like
    this (e.g.  you don't care whether your audio-rips are 100% OK or not,)
    then don't use GRaBAtOR.  Then there are better choices for you out
    there.

    - You have to write @{" me " LINK About 26} an email.  :)  (see @{" About " LINK About})

  (see also @{" Bugs " LINK Bugs})

@ENDNODE
@NODE Bugs "Known bugs"

  @{b}Bugs:@{ub}

    None known yet.

    Remember: I cannot fix a bug when I don't know about it -> email me!

    Note:
      GRaBAtOR (in fact it's my precedor in ARexx of GRaBAtOR which) did not
      work correctly with a second-hand CDROM by Plextor (4x, caddy, made
      1994).  I don't know, if it will fail with all CDROMs of this series,
      or, even worse, with certain models of other manufacturers too.
      Although that one CDROM was able to rip tracks without any audible
      distortions (with other programs), it wasn't able to rip _any_ small
      part of music 100% error-free...  (Nothing against Plextor, I have no
      probs at all with their UltraPlex.)

  (see also @{" Drawbacks " LINK Drawbacks})

@ENDNODE
@NODE Requirements "Requirements"

  @{b}Requirements:@{ub}

  ∑ an Amiga, probably OS 2.0(4) (not tested under 2.0x) with about
  ∑ 1.3 MB free RAM and SCSI,
  ∑ SCSI-CDROM
  ∑ should run on a plain 68000  (not tested)

  Highly recommended, but not required:
  ∑ a fast SCSI host adapter
  ∑ a SCSI-CDROM which is capable of good-quality digital audio extraction
    (DAE) (for very faulty discs)
  ∑ the above, but with fast DAE
  ∑ some HD-space (for your audio-data)
  ∑ some scratched audio-discs  :)
  ∑ 3.8MB of RAM, for the "real" version  :-)

   Tested and developed on:
     A4040/40/PPC/233, OS3.0/3.1
     BSC A.L.F.3 (Oktagon2008) + OktaPussy
     Sony CDU-76S
     Plextor UltraPlex
     Teac CD-R55S

@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "It can't be simplier.  ;-)"

  @{b}Installation:@{ub}

  Minimal installation:
    None.  Just use GRaBAtOR from where it is right now (after you've
    unpacked the archive, of course).

  Full installation:
    Copy GRaBAtOR and it's documentation to your HD, prefered place for the
    main program is somewhere in the path ( e.g.  C: ).

  Note:
    You could create the two files ENV:GRaBAtORDevice and
    ENV:GRaBAtORUnit as well, but since these files aren't supported
    yet at the moment, don't bother with them.  (Sub-note:  Maybe I won't
    support these at all due to to the fact that GRaBAtOR has more and more
    options.  Probably Argue could help a lot here, but until now I didn't
    had the time to create a GUI with it.)



  @{b}Uninstallation:@{ub}

    Simply delete all GRaBAtOR-related files from your HD.

@ENDNODE
