@NODE Usage "How to use GRaBAtOR?"

  @{b}GRaBAtOR's template is:@{ub}


    DEVICE=D/K,UNIT=U/K,HELPTOC=TOC/S,INFILE=IN/K,OUTFILE=OUTDIR=OUT,RAW/S,
    DRIVEISLSB/S,DRIVEISMSB/S,REVERSE=REV/S,MODE/K,DONTSTRIPLEAD=DSL/S,
    DONTSTRIPTRAIL=DST/S,DONTCONT=DC/S,FORCECONT=FC/S,NOANSI=NA/S,
    ZEROOFFSET=ZO/K,NOERRORBUG=NEB/S,POSITION/M

  @{b}Options:@{ub}

    WARNING:
      In future versions the options and/or their behaviour may change!
      (see @{" Main " LINK Main 17})

    Note:
      The options aren't case-sensitive.

    DEVICE <device> or D <device>:
      The device you want to access.  Don't forget the keyword "DEVICE" (or
      simply "D") before the devicename.  The device is (as always)
      case-sensitive.
    UNIT <unit> or U <device>
      The unit you want to access.  Don't forget the keyword "UNIT" (or
      simply "U") before the unit-number.  May be 0 - 15.  (If you should
      need a wider range, email me.)
    HELPTOC or TOC
      Prints out some information about the disc.  If you want to rip all
      (audio-)tracks from a CD then you only need to call GRaBAtOR with
      HELPTOC and redirect the output to a file (e.g.  >RAM:exeme) and
      execute the file as a script.  GRaBAtOR skips all non-audio tracks in
      this mode.
    INFILE <infile> or IN <infile>
      Infile (instead of DEVICE + UNIT combination) Don't forget the keyword
      "INFILE" (or simply "IN") before the filename.  (not supported yet)
    <output>
      The audio-sample(s) will be stored at this place.  This can either be
      a directory or a file or STDOUT. (stdout not tested yet) (see also @{" here " LINK Usage 158})
    RAW
      Use raw CDDA-files instead of the default AIFF-files.  Byte-order
      won't be changed if you use this flag.  Otherwise (in AIFF-mode) the
      byte-order will be reversed.  (see note on the byte-order @{" here " LINK Usage 143})
    DRIVEISLSB or LSB
      If your CDROM isn't supported by GRaBAtOR, you have to provide this
      information.  Should be self-explaining.  In most cases you'll
      probably use DRIVEISLSB (instead of DRIVEISMSB).  (see note on the
      byte-order @{" here " LINK Usage 143})
    DRIVEISMSB or MSB
      (see @{" above " LINK Usage 43}))
    REVERSE
      Shortly:  In most cases you won't need this switch.
      Detailed: @{" here " LINK Usage 143})
    MODE <STEREO|JOINED|LEFT|RIGHT|>
      Specify what kind of audio-data you want to write to <output>.
    DONTSTRIPLEAD or DSL
      Don't strip leading zeroes (see @{" note " LINK Usage 121}) below)
    DONTSTRIPTRAIL or DST
      Don't strip trailing zeroes (see @{" note " LINK Usage 121}) below)
    DONTCONT or DC
      Overwrite the existing outfile without trying to continue it.
    FORCECONT or FC
      If the existing outfile could be continued in more ways, GRaBAtOR will
      let you chose, which guess is the right one.  For this case you need
      to specify all the right options when you call GRaBAtOR to continue
      the file, plus this switch.  If you specify different parameters than
      those that GRaBAtOR would guess, the program fails with an
      error-message (even with this switch). (see also @{" here " LINK Usage 130}))
    NOANSI
      Self-explaining. Disables ANSI-codes in the messages.
    ZEROOFFSET <zerooffset> or ZO <zerooffset>
      I didn't found a better name for it in the hurry.  Mhhh, how to
      explain.  On some (most?) audio-CDs the TOC claims, that an
      audio-track starts at block x.  But in fact it may start y blocks
      later.  In a much worst case the track starts y blocks *earlier* than
      the TOC claims.  In that case (under normal conditions) it wouldn't be
      possible for the zero-detection routines to strip zeroes, because the
      TOC points somewhere *into* the track (where we can find anything but
      zeroes).  If zero-detection at point x fails, it will be tried at the
      points x - zerooffset and x + zerooffset too.  if x - zerooffset < y <
      x + zerooffset, everything will be fine, e.g.  we can strip the
      zeroes.  (Biggest zerooffset I've ever seen until now is 20.)
      <zerooffset> is a number from from 0 - 40.  Default is 20 for tracks
      and (it *must be*) 0 for anything else.  Ignored when both
      DONTSTRIPLEAD and DONSTSTRIPTRAIL given.
    NOERRORBUG or NEB
      IMPORTANT!  Use this switch if you have a scratched CD, but GRaBAtOR
      seems to find no errors, or it claims, it could avoid all upcoming
      errors (e.g.  you never see "Errors left:" in your display), and the
      output-file is crap!!  Then your drive suffers from a condition as my Teac
      drive does.  On scratched discs GRaBAtOR should detect lots of errors
      on the disc, and it is *not* normal, when under these circumstances
      the program doesn't detect any errors at all!  However, you should use
      this switch *only* if your drive really _needs_ it, because this
      switch makes GRaBAtOR *much* slower (especially on faulty discs).  If
      your drive still does not report errors while reading CDDA, then mail
      @{" me " LINK About 26}, I should be able to easily fix it.
    POSITION
    ∑ OFFSET <TRACK <nooftracks>|BLOCK[S] <noofblocks>|TIME <mm:ss:ff>>
    ∑ START  <TRACK <trackno>|BLOCK <blockno>|TIME <mm:ss:ff>>
    ∑ LENGTH <TRACK <nooftracks>|BLOCK[S] <noofblocks>|TIME <mm:ss:ff>>
    ∑ STOP   <TRACK <trackno>|BLOCK <blockno>|TIME <mm:ss:ff>>
      While TRACK <trackno> and BLOCK <blockno> and TIME should be
      self-explaining, mm:ss:ff is explained as follows:  mm = minutes, ss =
      seconds, ff = frames.  (One frame = 1/75th of a second thus, ff must
      be in a range from be 0 to 74.) Note:  In conjunction with OFFSET and
      STOP, TIME (as well as TRACK and BLOCK) is absolute.  With START it is
      relative to OFFSET, and with LENGTH it is relative to OFFSET and
      START.  Quite easy.
    ∑ OFFSET is meant for skipping a certain amount of data at the beginning
      of the disc, default is 0.
    ∑ START means the first unit given we need. (must be given)
    ∑ STOP declares the first given unit that isn't needed anymore.  (e.g.
      START 100000 STOP BLOCK 123456 means, that we need only blocks 100000
      until and including block 123455, and *not* until and including block
      123456, same with tracks, e.g.  START TRACK 1)
    ∑ LENGTH is much simplier, it gives the amount of data (minus header) we
      we'll get in <output>. Default LENGTH is "TRACK 1", which means 1 track.
      (see also @{" here " LINK Usage 136})


  Note on stripping zeroes:
    GRaBAtOR will only strip full blocks, and it's possible that you'll get
    one block at the beginning and one block at the end with some zeroes in
    them.  But as these two blocks are each 1/75th of a second, this doesn't
    really hurt.  The two advantages of this behaviour are:  1.  all
    non-zero blocks remain untouched, and 2.  the output (minus AIFF-header)
    will be always dividable by the blocksize.  (I'm told, that e.g. MakeCD
    doesn't like odd sized audio-files.)

  Note on continuing an existing outfile:
    By default GRaBAtOR tries to continue the given outfile.  It first tries
    to guess the parameters used for creation of the outfile.  If it can't
    guess it or if there are too many possibilities, it will fail with an
    error-message.

  Notes on the POSITION parameter:
   1. No illogical combinations allowed.  (e.g.  either LENGH or STOP not
      both, etc.)
   2. If you specify OFFSET, START, LENGTH or STOP multiple times,
      hopefully the last one should be used (*IX-style) (not tested), but
      take attention on the first note above.

  Note on the byte-order (REVERSE) in AIFF and raw files (RAW) in
  conjunction with a drive that gives LSB-MSB (intel) or MSB-LSB (motorola)
  output (DRIVEISLSB & DRIVEISMSB):
    Most drives return LSB-MSB pairs of CDDA-data, but my
    AIFF-implementation (btw, should be the same output as AsimCDFS's
    output) _requires_ MSB-LSB pairs of data.  So I decided to _always_
    reverse the byte-order by default for AIFF files (*only*), and leave RAW
    data unchanged.  (If you're using your CDR for reading and writing the
    same CDDA-data, then normally it is of no matter whether the RAW data is
    MSB-LSB or LSB-MSB, because the drive simply writes back everything
    exactly as it was readen before.) If you want to change this behavour
    for both AIFF _and_ RAW files, then specify th switch REVERSE.  (As this
    can cause lots of confusion, I'll probably change this in the future.
    Ummm, the first step is DRIVEISLSB and DRIVEISMSB)

  Note on <output>:
    In HELPTOC-mode <output> must be a dir (terminated with a ':' or a '/',
    else it will be truncated to a dir).  In any other mode <output>
    currently must be a file, else "GRaBAtOR<TRACKNUMBER>.#?" will be
    appended to <output>.


  @{b}Examples:@{ub}

    ∑ GRaBAtOR DH3:GRaBAtOR.out START TRACK 3
      Rips the whole third track (from the unit specified in
      ENV:GRaBAtORUnit) (of the device specified in ENV:GRaBAtORDevice) and
      stores the AIFF-audio-data in DH3:GRaBAtOR.out.  If ENV:GRaBAtORDevice
      does not exist, then the device is auto-guessed.  (ENV:GRaBAtOR#?
      aren't implemented yet)
    ∑ GRaBAtOR DEVICE oktagon.device UNIT 6 DH3: START TRACK 6
      Rips the whole sixth track and stores the data in DH3:GRaBAtOR06.aiff
    ∑ GRaBAtOR unit 4 DH4:
      Rips *every* audio-track from the CD (device see @{" above " LINK Usage 169}) and stores
      each AIFF-file in DH4:GRaBAtOR#?.aiff (not supported yet)
    ∑ GRaBAtOR unit 4 START TRACK 4 LENGTH TIME 1:24:74
      Rips from the beginning of the fourth track until (and including) the
      74th frame at 1:24 of track 4.
    ∑ GRaBAtOR OFFSET TRACK 3 START BLOCK 1000 LENGTH BLOCK 500
      Rips blocks 1000 to (and including) 1499 from track 3
    ∑ GRaBAtOR [OFFSET] TRACK 3 TIME 0:14 <outfile>
      Rips the 14th second _only_ of track 3 (not implemented yet)
    ∑ GRaBAtOR UNIT 6 TIME 2
      Rips the second minute from the beginning of the CD. (not implemented
      yet)
    ∑ GRaBAtOR UNIT 6 BLOCK 100500 LENGTH BLOCKS 2000
      Rips 2000 blocks beginning with (and including) block 100500 of the
      CD.
    ∑ GRaBAtOR OFFSET TRACK 0 [TRACK|BLOCK|TIME]
      Rips the (one, whole) given unit, counting from the beginning of the
      disc (not implemented yet)

  Now have fun with GRaBAtOR!


  Not yet implemented:

    GOODONLY (NOERRORS) (-f (force)) -> Don't give me erraneous data
      whatever may come.  (CTRL-c to stop  :) (not implemented)
    TRIES <n> - Accept erraneous data (and write that bad data to disk)
      after n(*100) (?n = 0 -> unlimited?) unsuccesful tries (see option
      NOERRORS).   Default  is n = 2 (= 200 tries on each bad data).  (I was
      too lazy yet to let the user specify this value.) The smaller this
      value the more bad data you'll probably get.  Note:  GRaBAtOR will not
      be slower when this value is set to(o) high and the CD is OK.
    NOROUND - turns off rounding up output filelength to an even blocksize.
      (This means max.  2*(blocksize-samplelength) zero-bytes could be
      stripped more.) Don't use this option if you are not sure about what
      you are doing!  (Not even planned, I've dropped this idea.  It isn't
      worth the effort, see elsewhere)
    NOAUDIOCHECK (NOTRACKCHECK) - Doesn't care if the track is an
      audio-track or not.  (Rips track even if it is not an audio-track.)
      (Tries to rip the data regardless of it's tracktype.) GRaBAtOR by
      default rips (parts of) audio-tracks only.  (not implemented)
    NOCENT - Turns automatic centralizing off (not implemented yet)
    NONORM - Turns automatic normalizing off (not implemented yet)
    NOEJECT - Prevents GRaBAtOR from putting the CD in and out (see below).
      (not implemented yet)
    NOSTOP - Won't help your drive against overheating during reads (not
      implemented yet)

@ENDNODE
@NODE History "Program history"

  @{b}Program history:@{ub}

  0.1alpha ('99.06.10) Not released.
    Trying to rewrite my good, old (and unreleased) ARexx-script in C.  Gone
    trough all that SCSI-stuff, the next parts should make more fun now.
  0.2alpha ('99.06.11) Not released.
    Seems to work...  CDDA support done (Motorola + intel).  In fact I've
    added just an option to reverse the byte-order.  ToDo:  Make it more
    intelligent
  0.3alpha ('99.06.11) Not released.
    JOINED mode added.
  0.4alpha ('99.06.13) Not released.
    AIFF support added.  It's a way dirty implementation, but who cares.
    Still ToDo:  zero-stripping and automatic byte-order detection, rewrite
    the whole thing for start vs.  end
  0.5alpha ('99.06.19) Not released.
    Thought I've gone trough all that SCSI-stuff, but I didn't.  :-( God,
    I'm damned slow, I should stop watching ST TNG & Co.  20-30 lines today.
    That's really no fun.  Grmpf.  I'm writing more on the docs then on the
    program itself.
  0.6alpha ('99.06.21) Not released.
    Strips leading zeroes (and whatever you declare as a leading zero).
  0.7alpha ('99.06.26) Not released.
    Zero-strip at beginning/end didn't work correctly.
  0.8alpha ('99.06.26) Not released.
    Umm, where shall I begin.  O.K., Finally it is here.  Error-free mode.
    Also available:  GRaBAtOR Light (in fact it is the last V0.x), which
    does not contain error checking, but zero-stripping and JOINED mode are
    available.  Lots of bugfixes/changes/cosmetic things.  Many things
    rewritten.  ;-( But my first impressions are very good.  Probably slower
    than needed.  Currently it produces _lots_ of debugging information.
    Oh.  I'm loosing some bytes somewhere.  I think I've found it.
  0.9alpha ('99.06.27) Not released.
    Hmmm.  I didn't sleep for 48h now.  This damn thing...  At least it
    seems to make exactly what I wanted to.  And it sucks the data from the
    (damaged) disc like a thunder (in comparsion to it's precedor :)).
    Added minworklen, this allows you to tell GRaBAtOR how big the smallest
    part may be.  GRaBAtOR adapts it's worklength automatically to the discs
    status.  O.K., 'night everyone.
  0.10alpha ('99.07.02) Not released.
    When the program encountered erraneous data while stripping the trailing
    zeroes then it could strip less zeroes than required.  Bug fixed.  NOTE:
    As GRaBAtOR does not try to correct (e.g.  interpolate) the zeroes (and
    the whole sample at all) (yet?), it still cannot decide, if these
    erraneous bytes among those zeroes are supposed to be zeroes or not.  If
    that's the case, it _is_ possible that the program might strip off less
    zeroes than it would w/o errors between the zeroes.  (I mean the
    first/last errors between leading/trailing zeroes will be treated as the
    beginning/end of the audio-data.  In this case you will get on the
    begining/end of the file more zeroes than you would get if there where
    no errors while stripping zeroes, but this shouldn't hurt that much.)
  0.11alpha ('99.07.04) Not released.
    New style argument-parsing.  Now you can select raw CDDA support with
    the corresponding command-line option RAW.  Cosmetic changes.
  0.12alpha ('99.07.05) Not released.
    Decided not to support GRaBAtORLight in any way.  Added options
    DONTSTRIPLEAD=DSL and DONTSTRIPTRAIL=DST.  Added a cool HELPTOC option
    :-).  Cosmetic changes.
  0.13alpha ('99.07.05) Not released.
    Output can be a file or stdout as well.  (All messages are sent to
    stderr).  New feature introduced:  Continuing of a previous file.
    IMPORTANT NOTEs and WARNINGs.  New option:  FORCECONT.  GRaBAtOR becomes
    more and more nice.  I hope there isn't contained any bug in this late
    alpha state.  GRaBAtOR is becoming beta very soon!
  0.14alpha ('99.07.07) Not released.
    Written on the docs.  Changed programs behaviour accordingly to what the
    docs say.  After a long, looong time visit at the dentist.  "I have done
    that tooth exactly as it should have been done, but it's one thing how I
    have done it, and another thing how you clench your teeth." Hmmm...  I'm
    feeling like a monster.  *lol* Prepared for different blocksizes.  Built
    a (very small) list of drives, for which I know what kind of
    raw-CDDA-data they deliver.
  0.15alpha ('99.07.10) Not released.
    Docs rewritten in AmigaGuide-format.  .aiff or .raw will only be
    appended if not there already.  Time to release the whole thing.
  0.16alpha ('99.07.11) Not released.
    German guide added.  (not finished yet) Hungarian guide added.  (not
    finished yet) Hmmm...  I cannot release GRaBAtOR yet due to some
    Problems in the phone-central caused by the phantastic
    weather-conditions here.  ("Water, water every where, And all the boards
    did shrink; Water, water every where, nor any drop to drink." Samuel
    Taylor Coleridge, but I wanted to quote Steve Harris.  :-) At least I
    have my miggy here up and running...  *sigh* Woah, I have the net on the
    other end of the wire.  Making some final arrangements...  Too bad, that
    I'm too tired to continue.
  0.17alpha ('99.07.12) Not released.
    Woah.  Found a bug in the MODE routine.  It was always set to STEREO.
    :-( (Now you know which mode I'm mostly using.  :) Quickly added some
    ugly icons for the docs.
  0.18Ŗ ('99.07.18) Not released.
    Fixed a bug when STOP was given, but LENGTH wasn't and the program
    claimed we've given both.  Bug fixed where program refused to overwrite
    a file.  Ooops.  Fixed "Out of range" -bug when stripping trailing
    zeroes from the last blocks of a disc.
  0.19Ŗ ('99.07.19) Not released.
    tracktype().  block2track().  Delay on error.  DRIVEISMSB/DRIVEISLSB.
    Cleanup.  Exe became shorter.  Major speedup on very faulty discs by
    adapting worklen properly.  Woah, by accident launched two GRaBAtOR's at
    the same time from the same faulty disc.  Ummm...  Looks good.  :)
    ANSI-messages.
 0.20Ŗ ('99.07.21) Not released.
    Able to find "hidden" leading/trailing zeroes.  Improved detection of
    start/end of a track (only if leading/trailing zero-detection enabled
    and ZEROOFFSET != 0).
 0.21Ŗ ('99.07.22) Not released.
     "Eject on error" feature added and tested.  (disabled in this version)
    I'm *amazed* how this helps in reading faulty discs!  I can't believe
    it...  (Might vary with other drives, though.) Much faster than my
    ARexx-script (which relayed on an other program to detect discchanges
    when the disc was re-inserted automatically, and that was *very* slow).
    Extended method of "hidden"-zero-stripping.  Didn't work properly with
    my Teac (drive couldn't report errors inside CDDA-track as expected),
    fixed.  Major speedup for faulty discs temporarily lost due to the
    Teac-workaround.
 0.22Ŗ ('99.07.28) First official public pre-release
    Lost speedup (introduced in 0.21Ŗ) regained.  Stripping zeroes is even
    more perfect (...and *terribly* slow).  Workaround for CDROM-hangup on
    _very_ faulty discs added, where drive sometimes refuses to recognize
    disc.  (disabled in the release) Workaround for Teac-style drives is
    called NOERRORBUG now, and can be disabled due to major
    speed-improvements on drives which does not suffer from this condition.
    Small cosmetic changes, and here we go.

